<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-922-170  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 922 170.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 19 1989 n1186 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Scorched software: who wins in court? (software copyright issues)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kemp, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software copyright litigation traditionally has involved fourelements: subsistence, ownership, duration and infringement.andP;  Inthe UK the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988 providesguidelines on each element.andP;  Problems arise, however, not whencode is copied, but rather when a program duplicates another's'look and feel.' In the US, where look and feel cases abound,Whelan Assoc won a precedent case when a court ruled there hadbeen infringement based on similar software functionality andinput formats.andP;  That and other cases marked a move towardsubjective copyright assessment on a case-by-case basis.andO;Corporations have adopted litigation as corporate policy toprotect shareholder interests.andP;  Cases are often slow-moving andinvolve many interrelated decisions.andP;  The still-pending Appleversus Microsoft over Windows is the most widely publicized ofsuch cases.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Whelan Associates Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     CopyrightCourt CasesLegal IssuesLaw SuitLegislationSoftware Packages.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Court cases concerning software copyrights. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>